{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2c3e2327-c80b-481d-84e4-1a4cca7d6eee","content":"In your `App.xaml.cs`, override `CreateWindow` and subscribe to the lifecycle events on the returned `Window`:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Created\");\n    window.Activated     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Activated\");\n    window.Deactivated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Deactivated\");\n    window.Stopped       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Stopped\");\n    window.Resumed       += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Resumed\");\n    window.Destroying    += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Destroying\");\n    window.Backgrounding += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine(\"Window Backgrounding\");\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Event flow:**\n\n| Transition | Events fired |\n|---|---|\n| App launch | `Created` → `Activated` |\n| User switches away | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |\n| User returns | `Resumed` → `Activated` |\n| App closed | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` → `Destroying` |\n| iOS backgrounding | `Backgrounding` (save state via `e.State`) |\n\n> **Note:** `Backgrounding` is iOS-only and provides a state dictionary for preserving data across termination.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8e56ed5d-7779-4e13-9623-dc165185e9f3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI Window lifecycle events and how to subscribe to them for debugging/logging purposes. This is a general programming knowledge question, not related to a specific codebase. I can answer this directly from my knowledge.","outputTokens":434,"requestId":"044F:B86C3:AC446B:C51780:6A027A0F"},"id":"0789d321-6957-46c5-aa19-b975ce2a4a5a","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:53:43.551Z","parentId":"e669f1fb-ebeb-471c-b5ca-ad85053eaafd"}
